1.2 Prior predictive simulation

for the full model of heights (ie. the model block in stan)

prior_mu <- rnorm( 1e4 , 178 , 20 )
prior_sigma <- rexp( 1e4 , 1/10)
prior_indv <- rnorm( 1e4 , prior_mu , prior_sigma ) #sampling from vectors of mu and sigma, 1 sample from each element?
plot(density(prior_mu))
lines(density( prior_indv), col = 'blue') #wider curve for individual obserations

The data is the height, weight, age and a categorical variable indicating whether the individual is male or female.

It is best practice to keep the data outside of the environment.

setwd("./2. linear regression")
xbar <- mean(d$weight)
N = length(d$weight)

plot(d$height ~ d$weight)

2.2 Prior Predictive Simulation

What are the reasonable prior assumptions on the beta coefficients?

For the intercept, we can also use prior information to assume that the average weight is around 178 lbs.

For the slope, we can assume that weight and height are positively correlated. Therefore, we can use the log-normal distribution to restrict the effects to positive values.

We can use these two pieces of information to set our priors for alpha and beta.

A prior predictive simulation simulates N regression lines for the effect of weight on height.

set.seed(2971)
N <- 100 # 100 lines
a <- rnorm( N , 178 , 20 ) #prior for alpha
b <- rlnorm( N , 0 , 1 ) #log normal prior for beta, to restrict effect of weight on height to be positive

We can visualize our prior predictive simulations using the code below.

#all the code below must be run as a chunk
plot(NULL, xlim=range(d$weight), ylim=c(-100,400), xlab="weight", ylab="height" )
abline(h=0, lty=2); abline(h=272, lty=1, lwd=0.5)
mtext("b ~ dlnorm(0,10)")
xbar <- mean(d$weight)
for (i in 1:N ) 
  curve(a[i] + b[i]*(x - xbar),
    from=min(d$weight), to=max(d$weight), add=TRUE, col=col.alpha("black",0.2))

2.3 Fitting the Model

The Stan script is written outside of the environment and is read in using the code below. Note that weight is centered.

setwd("./2. linear regression")
writeLines(readLines("linear_regression.stan"))
## data{
##     int<lower=1> N;
##     real height[N];
##     real weight[N];
##  real xbar;
## }
## parameters{
##     real a;
##     real b;
##     real<lower=0> sigma;
## }
## model{
##     vector[N] mu;
##     sigma ~ exponential( .1 );
##     b ~ lognormal( 0 , 1 );
##     a ~ normal( 178 , 20 );
##     
##     for ( i in 1:N ) {
##         mu[i] = a + b * (weight[i] - xbar);
##     }
##     height ~ normal( mu , sigma );
## }
## generated quantities{
##     vector[N] y_pred;
##     vector[N] mu;
##     
##     for ( i in 1:N ) {
##         mu[i] = a + b * (weight[i] - xbar);
##     }
##     
##     for (i in 1:N) {
##       y_pred[i] = normal_rng(mu[i], sigma);
##     }
## }
setwd("./2. linear regression")
data <- read_rdump("linear_reg.data.R") #import data
setwd("./2. linear regression")
fit <- stan(file='linear_regression.stan', data=data, seed=194838, chains = 1, warmup=1000, iter=10000)

2.6 Regression interval

Regression interval- conditional on x

mu_at_50 <- posterior$a + posterior$b*(50-xbar) #if x = 50
plot(density(mu_at_50))

HPDI(mu_at_50) #still works outside of "rethinking" object!
##    |0.89    0.89| 
## 158.5765 159.6688

Regression interval- (across all x).

You can use the link function to do this, or just create a matrix object below.

#create object
weight.seq <- seq( from=25 , to=70 , by=1 )
obj <- matrix(0, nrow=nrow(samples), ncol=length(weight.seq))
for (i in 1:20)
  for (j in 1:46)
    obj[i,j] <- (samples$a[i] + samples$b[i]*(weight.seq[j]-xbar))

Summarize the distribution of mu at each value of x.

mu.mean <- apply( obj , 2 , mean )
mu.HPDI <- apply( obj , 2 , HPDI , prob=0.89 )
plot( height ~ weight , data=d , col=col.alpha(rangi2,0.5) ) # plot raw data 
lines( weight.seq , mu.mean ) # plot the posterior regression line
shade( mu.HPDI , weight.seq ) # plot a shaded region for 89% HPDI

2.7 Prediction intervals

Simulating observations.

plot(density(posterior$`y_pred[1]`))

#or you can generate in R
weight.seq <- 25:70
mu.link <- function(weight) posterior$a + posterior$b*( weight - xbar )
sim.height <- sapply( weight.seq , function(weight)
  rnorm(
    n=nrow(posterior) ,
    mean=posterior$a + posterior$b*( weight - xbar ) ,
    sd=posterior$sigma ) )
height.PI <- apply( sim.height , 2 , PI , prob=0.89 ) #uses fn from rethinking... you can also use quartile...

Plotting

plot( height ~ weight , d, col=col.alpha(rangi2,0.5) ) #regression line
lines( weight.seq , mu.mean ) # draw HPDI region for line
shade( mu.HPDI , weight.seq ) # draw PI region for simulated heights
shade( height.PI , weight.seq )
